76561197970887820,Recommended,251830,9290596,"Posted: 28 February, 2014",all,Mandrake42,"""Stick it to the Man"" is hands down one of the most hilarious and original games I have played this year. Poor Ray, a bit of a shlub, being in the wrong place at the wrong time, ends up with a telekinetic/telepathic alien stuck inside his head. On the run from a shady government organization he has to use his new found powers to read the minds of everyone around him, steal the thoughts from their minds and then use them to solve the obstacles between him and safety. The writing is some of the best I've seen in a long time, even just eavesdropping on people who have no relevance to your current obstacle is well worth the laughter it brings. There is a trailer. Go watch it, then go buy the game. The kind of cleverness and creativity on display here puts me in mind of Double Fine at their finest. If you miss out on this, your world is a sadder and darker place and I pity you."
76561198135753955,Recommended,251830,29018496,Posted: 4 January,all,Arielrocks5,"For the record, I have no clue why this game is called ""Stick it to The Man"" even if you don't end up sticking anything to him throughout the entire game and the titular ""man"" doesn't become a promint figure until the final chapter. But I think ""Weird Wavy Purple Hand Sticking out of Head and sticking various stickers onto other objects and backgrounds"" would have been too long of a title.Anyway, this is my first time really reviewing a game (I'm mostly a film reviewer, so I'm sorry if I seem a bit out of touch and this review itself being all over the place) and I figured it would be of one I got during the big sale recently and thought was worth talking about.I never heard of this game until the sale and even then, I did it mostly because it was cheap and thought it looked cute enough. ""Stick it to The Man"" tells the story of Ray, a guy who lives in a world made up entirely out of paper materiel and stickers. After getting hit on the head, he suddenly wakes up with a big purple hand sticking out of his head and now has the ability to read minds and pull down various objects in the backgrounds and foregrounds.It's pretty straight forward in terms of gameplay: grab objects, stick them to others, run, jump, read minds of anyone to figure out what thing to stick on them, etc and etc.Oh, and you also must avoid being caught by henchmen of ""The Man"" in these small segments that appear every now and then in chapters, along with using your purple hand to grab onto thumbtacks as a grappling hook.It's decently done and kept me playing, but it's nothing I doubt many familiar with adventure games or platformers will think is breaking any new grounds. Puzzles are fairly easy to figure out (but still rather fun to do so) and for the most part, the levels go by in a snap if you know what you need to do with certain stickers and characters.In the grand scheme of things, Gameplay doesn't really seem to main focus of the team behind this. The main focus seems to be mostly on the various types of quirky characters and very odd scenarios/solutions for puzzles and see how many laughs they can get out of the player.I can't really say this game is flat out hilarious or even THAT much nuanced to the weird comedy genre, but there's something oddly charming about it.The art direction looks like ""The Simpsons"" meets ""Psychonauts"" with this odd cardboard and paper aesthetic that's equal parts fun to look at and very bizarre, along with the soundtrack, which is pretty fun too (give ""Get me a Shrink!"" a listen to if you're in the mood for some funky jazz)The writing in general kept me consistently chuckling and laughing through, but I dunno, it all feels.......token? Like, I've felt like I've seen these types of punchlines before but I can't put my finger on where exactly (it could be Matt Groening, Tim Schafer, or Dan Povenmire, but it could be something else entirely), but they're still funny and it made me want to see where it would go next.Voice acting is pretty solid across the broad, but there's some moments (mostly during jokes) that the timing of the punchlines feel a bit off, which for a comedy game is a pretty big fail, but it doesn't happen as often as I was dreading.The weird characters you meet throughout the journey are pretty interesting to watch in the ""what the hell is going to be the outcome for him/her?"" sorta way and the game itself ends on a fairly nice punchline.If there's any other issue in regards to gameplay, I would say the segments with the henchmen get pretty tedious after awhile and it's often annoying to be reading the mind of one, only to then have them walk out of the frame you can do so as they charge over to you, with a small delay between moments of getting in control again.I would say as well it's A BIT over priced (?) for four hours of standard Adventure Game stuff if that's what you're looking for, but if you're looking for a breezy, simple, and charming little time killer, stick this one into your chart.7/10"
,Recommended,251830,31419720,Posted: 28 April,all,waelhadaya,"Stick it to the Man is funky, colorful and elegant piece of game, it’s a mixture of “point and click” and light platforming, all though it’s pushed back slightly by the short length and the annoying chase sections.I like the paper graphics here, it’s so elegant and cheerful, the music is beautiful and spot on that it couldn’t get better actually, the puzzles are fun to solve, and the atmosphere will get you hooked in immediately.The characters are memorable and light hearted, almost every dialogue is funny, it’s full of comedy and unique humor, it never failed to make me smile the whole way through (especially the Elvis guy, and the beep beep boob beep robot).I would say it could have been better with a higher score in my opinion if it wasn’t short, 5 hours for a play through is arguably short for my taste, also the chasing sections are nothing but annoying, it felt like an afterthought by the developer to add more gameplay elements I guess which the game lacks anyway.I do recommend this game, it’s awesome, I rate it a sticky 7 out of 10."
76561198027931146,Recommended,251830,11188999,"Posted: 11 July, 2014",all,Man with a Stick,"This game was one of the best adventure games I've ever played. The jokes were close by, each of them funny and punchy. The music was fun - most of it wasn't memorable at all, yet it fit perfectly, but the title song was magic. The art was unique, original, fun, and throughout the game world are little background and foreground jokes that add a bit of spice to an already fantastic looking game. Characters were lively, silly, voiced EXCELLENTLY, their inner thoughts giving way to some very good jokes - it's little homages to gaming were tasty icing to naturally good comedy - that actually handle scat humour with real wit. You learned to love our little protagonist and his head... thing. While the puzzles were strange, they made sense, and the wonderful thing about this game that they were solved simply by curiously peeking into peoples thoughts everywhere you went, and you wouldn't play this game if you didn't want to do that. And, like many other people, the game is actually fun for the brief sections where you run from the guards. Those parts get harder with a proper curve, and are fun, and briefly exhilirating. It was a nice way to counter balance the slow puzzling. And the length? It had a story to tell, and it told it quickly. This kind of game was more like a movie than anything else, and the running gag can only last so long. So, by not making looong pointless areas, they condensed everything to a perfectly proportioned pie of funny and pictures and visual stimuli, with a quick, fun story. I wouldn't want it longer, because everything they did felt good. I didn't feel like I wanted more - was satisfied, and laughing. And that, with good voice acting, art style, jokes, pacing, gameplay, game mechanincs, characters, music, and identity, is really, all you can ask for, isn't it? And this game had all of that in SPADES. LARGE SPADES. SHOVELS, EVEN.10/10, Liked It, 5 Stars, 