,Not Recommended,251830,33289676,Posted: 5 July,all,General Kass,"A 2.5d puzzle platformer desperately trying to be Psychonauts, but without any interesting characters or gameplay.Aside from the obviously Double Fine inspired art direction, this game reminds me of Double Fine’s The Cave in how simplistic it’s puzzles are. Levels are long, self-contained 2.5 platforming sets, like The Cave. Single level puzzles ensure that everything will be wrapped up neatly and that there will never be a challenge. There aren’t even red herring puzzle items, like The Cave. Puzzles are extremely obvious due to the mind reading effect, which tells you the answer.For example: A dog says, “I wish I had teeth so I could bite these dudes” and by sheer coincidence you have a crocodile tooth sticker.There are only two scenarios in which you'll have a spare item and both of those are used for achievement related side-puzzles. The result is a puzzle game with no challenging puzzles.The jokes are really hit or miss and a lot of them are references. Yes, you did a Mario joke, well done; that horse was beaten into a red paste 20 years ago, what else do you got? Aside from “humorous” observations, the game's other running joke is giving animals antiquated Shakespearean accents and vocabularies that can only be discovered by reading their minds. It's funny the first time, but when every single animal talks like a Victorian-era art critic, it loses its charm faster than a Leprechaun on speed.Probably the biggest difference between The Cave and Stick it to the Man is the atmosphere. The Cave took place in dark empty areas with one or two NPCs. Stick it to the Man occurs in large city environments and is based on quietly helping other characters solve their problems. I was actually really impressed by one aspect: Most puzzles have a running theme of repairing unlikely relationships. Unfortunately, that's the game's only real source of inspiration and, paired with the frankly huge cast of one-dimensional characters, the atmosphere loses its charm faster than a Leprechaun on speed.The voice acting is just terrible. Let me explain. In voice work, characters have funny voices; funny voices don’t make characters. With little exception, every character has a similarly overextended speech pattern and a wacky accent which proves to be more distracting than funny or immersive.The main character's voice sounds like a cheese grater with a New York accent.In fairness though, some of the worst voice work comes from horrific dialogue writing.You’ll hear “I should have not stayed up all night LAST NIGHT eating burritos, yet I have no regret about eating burritos all night,” and similar lines about micro-naps dozens and dozens of times. This attempt at humor (its not really a joke) would only have been funny once, but the game design forces you to commit the greatest sin in all of comedy games: repeating the joke over and over and over and over again. It loses its charm faster than a Leprechaun on speed.Dr. Brom (who is based on Dr. Monroe from The Simpsons), the taxidermist, blue haired radio operator, and the mother are the only consistently good character voices in the entire game.Ray (the PC) and Ted (the alien that lives inside his head) are the worst voices, by far.Yet even the voice acting cannot compare to the hideous ""plot"" of this game. From the get go, the plot is essentially the PC being chased by bad guys. There's an apparent mystery with a psychologist (who Ray has never met before) but it doesn't go anywhere. Despite having a huge set up, nothing in this game's storyline has any pay off.  The antagonist makes a number of intro-cutscene apperances, but they don't amount to anything. You make it to the end of your 3 hour journey and nothing is gained. You don't know why the bad guy is evil and neither does he. Once he finally gets what he wants he say something to the effect of ""Why did I do this anyway?"" The antagonist is as confused as the player. The result is a comedy puzzle game that fails to be funny and has no interesting puzzles, but does have a host of one-dimensional characters, terrible voice acting, and a nonsense plot (even for a game that takes place in a world of stickers and cardboard).$15 for 3 hours of terrible puzzles, terrible writing, terrible voice acting, and a terrible story."
,Recommended,251830,9142502,"Posted: 16 February, 2014",all,McPoops,"For $15 (or less, depending on when you buy it) you get 5 hours of what can only be described as an absolute joy to look at.  Puzzles are fun and clever and while most of the humor is pretty lame, it's still very charming.  Definitely a good way to spend an afternoon."
76561198056879077,Not Recommended,251830,11042954,"Posted: 2 July, 2014",all,pickles4nickles,"Stick it to The Man! is... strange. It's a puzzle platformer that's more of a point-and-click, but neither of those facets of the game aren't super successful.The main mechanics of Stick it to the Man! are reading people's minds to gather information and manipulating the world by peeling off stickers and placing them on other things to solve problems, all while avoiding government agents out to get you.The mind reading part is tedious. The voice acting is great, but some characters speak very slowly and by the time you finish reading the subtitiles, the character is only halfway through his or her speech. Dialogue cannot be skipped in pieces or scrolled through, only sped up or skipped entirely.The puzzles themselves aren't anything special. One of the recurring ""puzzles"" (if you may call it that) is escaping the agents trying to get you. I didn't enjoy any of these segments. I'm assuming the game expects you to cleverly sneak around the enemies, placing stickers on them to make them fall asleep or distract them. However, this is usually impossible to do as you can't see all the agents on the screen at once and you have only a few seconds before they notice you and start chasing you around. It's much easier to just run to the other side than trying to spend time sticking stickers on people and getting caught.Stick it to the Man's strongest element is its art style. The character design is amazing as every character looks unique with a different personality. Everything has a cardboard or paper-y texture, but it's different than, say, Paper Mario. It's almost as if the game would be stronger as a cartoon instead of a video game, or maybe if the focus was more on a point-and-click style than a platformer.Overall, I don't think I can recommend this game as a game, but, if you like art and design, it might be worth it to at least try it."
